      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":52,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":392,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":392,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at the very easy end of your easy pace range. Let your body settle in — no rushing.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":42,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Comfortable conversational effort throughout. You should be able to speak in full sentences. Heart rate should stay well below threshold.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off in the final 5 minutes. Let your heart rate come down naturally.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin at a very relaxed walk-jog for the first 2–3 minutes before settling into your easy pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5 minutes of gentle jogging, then 3–4 lower-body stretches focusing on quads, calves, and hip flexors.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your aerobic foundation run — the workhorse of half marathon training. Running easy might feel almost too comfortable, and that's exactly right. Around 80% of your weekly volume should feel like this. These runs build your aerobic engine, improve fat oxidation, and promote recovery between harder efforts. There's no such thing as 'too slow' on an easy day.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"title\":\"Active Recovery Cross-Training\",\"target_distance_km\":0,\"target_duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":0,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":0,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":0,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Low-impact movement: cycling, swimming, yoga, or walking. Keep effort light — this is recovery, not fitness building. If your IT band feels tight, gentle hip and glute work is a great use of this time.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed. Ease straight into your chosen activity at a very light effort.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5–10 minutes of gentle stretching, paying particular attention to your IT band, glutes, and hip flexors given your history of IT band tightness.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Given your history of IT band tightness, keeping one day per week as low-impact cross-training is a smart investment. It keeps blood flowing for recovery without adding impact stress to your legs. Think of this as maintenance work — keeping the machine running smoothly. Cycling and swimming are both excellent choices here.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Threshold Tempo Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":352,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":293,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"10–12 minutes easy jogging. This isn't optional — your threshold system needs time to come online. Finish the warmup with 4–6 short strides of 15–20 seconds to prime the legs.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":293,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Comfortably hard — you can speak only in short phrases. This is your lactate threshold pace at 4:53/km. Aim for even effort, not even splits — if it's a hilly route, slow up hills and recover on the downs.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease back to easy pace for the final 10–12 minutes. Let your breathing return to normal before stopping.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"10–12 minutes of easy jogging followed by a few dynamic leg swings and 4–5 strides of 15–20 seconds each to prepare the neuromuscular system.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"10–12 minutes of easy jogging, then static stretches for calves, hamstrings, and hip flexors. Consider a foam roll of the IT band if you have access.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Threshold running is the cornerstone of half marathon fitness. Your threshold pace (4:53/km) is the speed at which lactate production just outpaces clearance — training at this effort pushes that point higher, meaning you can sustain faster paces before fatiguing. A 20-minute continuous tempo run is a solid dose for your current fitness. The effort should feel 'comfortably hard' — controlled, purposeful, but not desperate. If you have to fight for it, you're going too fast.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":9,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":352,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":270,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15 minutes easy jogging. Finish with 4–5 strides of 20 seconds at interval effort to prime the system before the main set.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":270,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 1000m at 4:30/km (interval pace). Each rep should feel hard but controlled — you're working at roughly 95–98% max HR by the end of each rep. Start conservatively; the 4th and 5th reps are where the adaptation happens.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"90-second to 3-minute easy jog or walk between each interval. The goal is to recover enough to hit the next rep at full quality — not to recover fully, but to recover sufficiently.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"10–12 minutes easy jogging to flush lactate and bring heart rate down gradually.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes of easy jogging is non-negotiable before intervals. Finish with 4–5 x 20-second strides at your target interval pace to prime the legs and reduce injury risk.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"At least 10–12 minutes of easy jogging after the final interval. Your cardiovascular system needs time to wind down safely. Follow with full lower-body stretching.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals are the performance sharpener in your training week. Running at 4:30/km stimulates your maximum oxygen uptake system — this is what builds the top-end aerobic capacity that makes your goal half marathon pace feel more manageable. Five 1km reps is a solid but not excessive dose for your fitness level. The key principle: each rep should feel roughly the same — if the first few feel easy, you're going too slow; if you're falling apart by rep 3, you started too fast. Aim for controlled discomfort.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Short Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":403,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":403,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Keep this at the very easy end of your easy range — 6:43/km or even slower is perfectly fine here. The day after intervals, your legs will be talking to you. Honor that. This run exists to promote blood flow and recovery, not to add fitness.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — the entire run is at easy effort. Begin with a 2–3 minute walk if your legs feel particularly heavy.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with light stretching, particularly calves and hip flexors. If your IT band feels any tightness, add 5 minutes of glute activation work (clamshells, side-lying leg raises).\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The day after your interval session, this short easy run acts as active recovery. It's tempting to skip it or to push the pace slightly — resist both urges. The easy effort promotes blood flow and light muscle flushing without adding stress. If you genuinely feel awful, it's okay to make this a walk or swap with the cross-training day. Listen to your body.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":15,\"target_duration_minutes\":100,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":392,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":392,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 8–10 minutes at the very easy end of your pace range. Your body needs time to warm up for a long effort — don't skip this even if you feel great.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":82,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable, conversational easy pace. For a 15km long run, aim to finish feeling like you could have gone a few more kilometers. The goal is time on feet and aerobic development — not speed. Stay at 5:52–6:43/km throughout.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 10 minutes, ease off to the very easy end of your range. Let your heart rate come down before you stop.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with 5 minutes of easy walking or very light jogging before settling into your long run pace. On long runs, the warmup is built into the first 10–15 minutes of the run itself.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 3–5 minutes after finishing, then spend 10 minutes on lower-body stretching: calves, hamstrings, hip flexors, quads, and glutes. Given your IT band history, include a gentle IT band stretch and foam rolling if available.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is the single most important workout of the week for half marathon preparation. At 15km this week (a modest step up from your recent 14km long run), you're building the aerobic base and muscular endurance that will carry you through race day. Key principles: run at a genuinely easy pace — your long run pace and your easy run pace are the same thing. If it feels too slow, that's correct. Fueling note: for runs approaching 75–90 minutes, you might consider taking water or a sports drink — this is a good time to start practicing your race-day fueling routine. This is your longest and most important day of the week, so protect your sleep and nutrition the night before.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
